A Redd Christmas

craigr244

Gene Redd Jr. Songwriter/Singer

Gene Redd came to my attention when I put together my Kool and the Gang page and learned that Redd occasionally contributed to some of the groups songs. Kool and Gang mostly co-wrote as a group often providing credits to the entire band.

Redd was a member of the Five Chimes and then the Fi-Tones. In 1966 he was an A&R producer for Musicor Records.

But perhaps Redds lasting legacy was his co-composition of Please Come Home for Christmas which he co-wrote with R&B singer Charles Brown.

No doubt that Gene Redd found his way to work at 1650 Broadway along with so many other Brill Building composers, especially his work with Don Kirshner and Dimension Records.

Charles Brown passed away on January 21st, 1999 at age 76. Gene Redd has also passed away. (date unknown).

Gene Redd Jr. Selected Discography

I have also included several recordings which were produced by Gene Redd Jr.  There are very likely many more Redd involved recordings which I didnt track down, but obviously, Redd was a busy composer/producer/arranger.

Theyre Fresh! (and Exciting!)

craigr244

Kool and the Gang

I hate to admit it but I had to develop a taste for Kool and the Gang and that taste came through a fellow employee and friend of mine, Robyn back in the 1970s.

Robyn kept a small boom box at his drafting table and generally after lunch time another employee, Gordy, would yell out Lets have some Kool and the Gang! That would be enough to get Robyn to crank up the boom box complete with a cassette tape slot and the office would be filled with the sounds of New Jersey!

Today I fondly look back to that time, those tunes and what was obviously some of the best soul music to ever arrive on our planet.

As far as chart success goes, Kool and the Gang rank well ahead of the Stylists, the Chi-Lites and amazingly, Earth, Wind and Fire, perhaps my favorite soul groups of the late 1960s and 1970s.

Kool and the Gang were truly talented instrumentalists who quickly caught the attention of the music industry. Their roots go back to their high school days in 1964 who first performed as the Jazziacs due to Jersey City, NJ being their home base.

The original found members were:

Robert Bell

Ronald Bell (deceased 2020)

Dennis Thomas (deceased 2021)

George Brown (deceased 2023)

Ricky West (deceased 1985)

Robert Mickens (deceased 2010)

Charles Smith (deceased 2006)

Over the life of the band more than 35 musicians played with Kool and the Gang.

An eighth member, Woody Sparrow, was with the group for one long play before departing.

Six of the above attended Lincoln High School. While they were playing in New Jersey, occasionally backing the likes of Pharoah Sanders and McCoy Tyner they used different names such as the Soul Town Band and the New Dimensions. In 1967 they briefly became Kool and the Flames until a name tweak was suggested due to the existence of James Browns Famous Flames. And so, the band was set forevermore as Kool and the Gang. Member Robert Bell was Kool.

Their manager, Gene Redd, who was also a songwriter, formed De-Lite Records and signed the band to a contract. Redd had teamed up with Charles Brown in 1960 to composed Please Come Home for Christmas, a song that charted 17 Times!

In the beginning, the band was primarily an instrumental group but then due to audience demands the group would begin to step up to the microphone to deliver vocals. That went very slow at first but they stuck to it, practiced and became very proficient.

A huge move in 1979 was the addition of vocalist James T. Taylor who was brought in for his singing ability. This paid off big time giving the group some of their biggest hits. Taylor remained with the band until 1988.

Eugene Record Soul Songwriter  The Chi-Lites

craigr244

The Chi Lites

When Janet and I settled in Merced, California after I returned from my one-year stint in Vietnam (1971), I had a lot of catching up to do with the music of the day. Back in Vietnam we had no internet, no streaming, limited radio (Armed Forces Radio) and very little access to the music that was hitting the charts.

This was the era of the singer/songwriters but was also a great time for smooth soul music.

VISIT MY SOUL TRAIN SERIES:

Soul Train  An Introduction

Soul Train  The Groups  Season 1  1971/1972

Soul Train  The Groups  Season 2  1972/1973

Soul Train  The Groups  Season 3  1973/1974

Soul Train  The Groups  Season 4  1974/1975

After I had time to check out much of what I had been missing, I quickly decided that the sweet sound of the Chi Lites on Have You Seen Her was more than pristine  It was perfect! And to cap it off they gave us Oh Girl in April of 1972, this time topping off both the R&B and Pop Charts!

The Chi Lites were high school friends in Chicago and began singing in 1959. By 1964 they had started recording on the Daran record label. From there they moved through the Blue Rock, Ja-Wes, Dakar, Revue and Daren labels.

As it turns out, the Chi-Lites didnt start happening while I was out of the U.S. In fact, they begin hitting the nations charts in early 1969. They really got to rolling with Have You Seen Her in October of 1971 when they hit the top spot on the R&B charts and the top ten on Billboards pop charts.

In 1964 they were called Marshall and the Chi-Lites. The would shorten the name later in the year and stick with that going forward.

The original members were:

Marshall Thompson 1959 to present (2024)

Eugene Record from 1959 to 1973 and 1980 to 1988 (deceased 2005)

Robert Lester from 1959 to 2010 (deceased 2010)

Creadel Jones from 1959 to 1973 (deceased 1995)

Clarence Johnson from 1959 to 1964 (deceased 2011)

The Chi-Lites would appear on Soul Train seven times from 19

Eugene Record Songwriter

Eugene Record was born Eugene Booker Record on December 23rd, 1940 in Chicago, IL.

Eugene will always be remembered as a founding member and lead singer of the Chi-Lites but also as a gifted songwriter. Two of his primary songwriting partners were soul singer Barbara Acklin and Carl Davis.

His first group would the Hi-Lites during high school in Chicago. Record would alternate recording solo and with the Chi-Lites and would follow Brunswick executive Carl Davis to the Chi-Sound record label in the 1980s.

Eugenes emotional Have You Seen Her was composed after his marriage to high school sweetheart Sandra Scott dissolved.

Eugene Record passed away losing a bought with cancer on July 22nd, 2005 at the age of 64.
